        Conclusion - Part III (End)<br/><br/>The slide on the screen appeared to disturb Steven and Ronald to the point that they were both getting a bit unnerved.<br/><br/>"What we have here is a black market for Huge Kingdom items that began with several key MMM employees." I explained. "We're going to talk about the specific actions in a later slide.  I'd like to stick to our timeline and show you the series of events that led to this.  Firstly, a key vulnerability in the Huge Kingdom inventory was discovered in the quality assurance process.  The vulnerability was discovered by Chuck, who then allowed Barbie to file it as a bug.  At this time, Chuck and Barbie had a semi-romantic relationship.  According to employee interviews, Barbie's skills were noticeably inadequate for her position.  Chuck was privy to this opinion and made every attempt to help Barbie appear like a functional part of the team - including providing her with bugs to file and the necessary background material to explain the bugs."<br/>I paused briefly to advance my slides.  Steven was holding his head in his hands.<br/><br/>"Secondly, Chuck never officially added the bug fix to the production builds of Huge Kingdom." I said.<br/><br/>"He added the fix to the CVS, however the fix wasn't complete." Scrap interjected.  "If you look at this slide carefully, you'll notice that there is code to clean the requests to the server-side inventory handler.  However, the code is intentionally broken.  The version of the code that would have fixed this is 1.0.4.  This code was copied into a 1.0.5 version, but a key sequence of code was removed which actually cleaned the requests." <br/><br/>"Exactly." I added.  "Chuck did this with the intention of providing Barbie with more opportunities to report critical bugs.  What appeared at one time to be a 'medium' level bug fix would later be found by Barbie to be a 'high' level bug fix."<br/><br/>"But how the hell did he do this under the nose of Duke when he was here?  Duke would have been employed at the time this happened." Steven asked.<br/><br/>"Duke spent his last weeks at MMM working on core engine components and fixes that never made it into the game.  With Duke distracted and upset by management not wanting to implement a lot of his suggestions, Chuck was doing all source and build management." I responded.  "The change control function failed miserably.  Management oversight was almost non-existent at this point." <br/><br/>Ronald glanced frequently at Steven, watching his reactions to my report.  It appeared that Ronald was not a happy CEO.<br/><br/>I moved on to the next slide.<br/><br/>"Looking at our timeline, Barbie has been moved to an administrative function at the request of Mr. Slinkpips.  I thought this move was strange, and asked several other members of the staff about it.  Are either of you aware that Mr. Slinkpips regularly attends after-hours happy hours with staff members?  Two employees revealed in their interviews that Mr. Slinkpips has been known to sing Karaoke with Barbie and a few other staffers.  You may have a possible conflict of interest in your human resources department." I said.<br/><br/>"Oh, lovely." Ronald moaned.  <br/><br/>"This next slide goes into a bit more detail about the slide we saw earlier.  This shows specific activities on Barbie's workstation that were captured by my associate.  You'll notice some key items here:<br/><br/>1) Barbie spent a lot of time playing the company product, which I understand is allowed by company policy.  You'll notice, however, that several in-game chat conversations were captured.  The software we installed was only able to catch Barbie's part of the conversation through her keystrokes.  These conversations are the same conversations that Ken had been recording for us as he followed our mischievous minotaur around Huge Kingdom - otherwise known as Trotsky.<br/><br/>2) You'll notice that several of the conversations are between Barbie and other characters.  From her side of the conversation, you can see that she is trying to arrange the sale of Huge Kingdom items.<br/><br/>3) On the following slide, you'll see captured eBay traffic that shows her account name 'hugekingdomwares', the posting of Huge Kingdom items for sale, and seller to buyer communications.  <br/><br/>4) Towards the bottom of the same slide, you'll see captured webmail traffic from hotmail.com.  Barbie has logged in as user 'trotsky' to read emails from Paypal indicating that payment has been received for several items.  You'll also see emails where Barbie has used the same account and funds to purchase items on Ebay."<br/><br/>Ronald interrupted me.<br/><br/>"Chief, I have to thank you for a very complete investigation of this matter.  To be quite honest, I've heard enough of this matter.  Steven is going to perform a little house cleaning for me.  If it's not too much to ask, I'd like you and your associate to stay and help us plug these holes in our product, staff and procedures."<br/><br/>I glanced at Scrap, who returned a nod.<br/><br/>"We'd be happy to assist, Ronald." I said as I shook Ronald's hand.<br/><br/>Ronald had a brief heated discussion with Steven and left the room.  <br/><br/>"If the information on your slide is accurate, they were using embedded commands to manipulate the inventory parser on the server.  I'd like to see this in action." Steven demanded.<br/><br/>"Allow me." Scrap said as he removed a laptop from his bag. <br/><br/>The demonstration was wildly successful.  Steven was completely aghast.<br/><br/>"So Barbie decided to take advantage of Chuck and her knowledge of this bug to make some cash on the side?  It just seems so risky." Steven said as he stared at Scrap's laptop.  <br/><br/>"There aren't too many more dangerous things in life than a woman scorned." I mumbled.<br/><br/>"Boy can I vouch for that." Scrap said in agreement.<br/><br/>Barbie and Chuck were interviewed by Steven and an attorney and terminated that same day. Ronald met with Slinkpips shortly after our meeting and severely reprimanded him.  Slinkpips somehow retained his position in the human resources department.<br/><br/>Scrap demonstrated the bug to the last remaining programmers and worked with the development team to squash the bug.  <br/><br/>After my presentation to MMM's legal department, they were very eager to implement safeguards immediately.  I spent my last few days on this engagement writing a security plan and policies for MMM, including an entire software development life cycle and change management program.  <br/><br/>=*=<br/><br/>The plane ride home couldn't have come soon enough.  Scrap and I were mentally exhausted and were planning some rest and relaxation time. <br/><br/>"That was the most bizarre engagement I've ever seen." I said as I sampled the free pretzels and questionable-quality coffee provided by the flight attendant.<br/><br/>"You got that right, man.  The whole thing was a bummer all the way around." Scrap said in between swigs of cola.<br/><br/>"What do you mean?" I asked.  "You looked like you were in your element there towards the end."<br/><br/>"Maybe so." Scrap said.  "But I would have really liked a date or two with Barbie.  Wowzers."<br/><br/>"You are unreal." I said as I tossed a pretzel at Scrap.
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer"></div>
